    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if i adjust the COGS to account for the lost stock, does that make the turnover ratio look better or worse? i'm trying to figure out if the theft is making us look more efficient because we're \"selling\" through less physical stock even though it's actually just gone.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Heavily adjusting COGS to account for shrinkage will likely make your inventory turnover ratio look *worse*, not better. Because you're removing inventory that never actually left the building, your Cost of Goods Sold will be artificially lowered relative to the actual sales you made. It's a deceptive trick, as a true turnover ratio measures how quickly you move *actual* goods. It's much better to address the shrinkage separately, perhaps by calculating a \"net realizable inventory\" figure.",
      "source": "target",
